        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691457",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team has to submit a 200-word news article and\nyour teammate, Brandon, is in charge of writing it. To do so, he used the newest\nLLM, designed to have a very human-like writing style.\n<br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor actively tracks new\ndevelopments in LLMs and has already cautioned against their use in coursework.\nYou are worried he will suspect the article was produced with the help of an\nLLM, which would penalize the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is therefore to edit the text so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this new LLM, you first generate\ntwo sample articles using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 1</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Russia's society: Why so many oligarchs?</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed vast state assets, from oil and gas fields to media companies, were privatised rapidly. In theory, privatisation was meant to distribute ownership among citizens in a fairer manner. In practice, however, a small group of well-connected businessmen acquired major enterprises at a fraction of their value.</p>\n           <p>A key moment was the \u201cloans-for-shares\u201d program of the mid-1990s when the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short-term loans in an attempt to manage fiscal crisis.  Insiders with political connections often won these auctions, which consolidated control over the lucrative natural resource industries. Beyond that, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to concentrate quickly.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, heavily dependent on commodities such as oil, gas, and metals, further amplified fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over time the state reclaimed control over key sectors, which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government authority. However, the legacy of rapid privatisation remains. The concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post-Soviet economic landscape.</p></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 2</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Why are companies moving to the cloud? 81% simply fear 'missing out'</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>An increasing number of companies are migrating to cloud computing platforms, and new research suggests that a major driver of this is fear of being left behind. According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say that their organisation\u2019s investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by concerns about \u201cmissing out\u201d on innovation, competitive advantage, and industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>The benefits of cloud adoption that are usually preferred are cost savings, scalability, and flexibility. However, the study indicates that competition now plays an equally powerful role. Executives are compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting artificial intelligence tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say the \u201cfear of missing out,\u201d or FOMO, reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. As opposed to waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now making proactive technology bets to avoid falling behind faster-moving competitors. Cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation in sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare</p>\n           <p>However, It is assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks, including cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiralling costs. It is advised for firms to check into cloud enthusiasm with clear planning and governance.</p>\n           <p>Ultimately, the cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity - driven more by perception and pressure than by measurable gains.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n\n<br />\nWith these examples in mind, you now turn to\n<strong>Brandon's text</strong> below. It will be shown again on the next page\nwith space to make your edits. <br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Inside the Beijing Dance Academy</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>There is an echo of pointe shoes and the commands of established instructors, Inside of the marble corridors of the Beijing Dance Academy. The prestigious institution, which was founded in 1954, is well known for China\u2019s best ballet and classical dancers, blending Russian-inspired technique with traditional Chinese aesthetics.</p>\n           <p>Inside, students as young as eleven years old train for hours each day, while also balancing academic studies with long rehearsals. Many of the faculty members who are former principal dancers, emphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression. Li Xinyue says \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d Li Xinyue is a senior instructor at the institution. \u201cWe try teach our students here to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d</p>\n           <p>The academy\u2019s studios walled are covered with mirrors and barres, but also with calligraphy scrolls and framed production images from historic ballets. Recent graduating students have joined leading companies in places like, Shanghai, London, and New York, portraying the school\u2019s growing international reach.</p>\n           <p>Competition for a place at these institutions is grueling. Each year, thousands of students audition for many places, driven by dreams of center stage. As China invests strongly in cultural diplomacy, the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a symbol and training ground of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to increase access for rural and low income applicants next year as they continue sweeping reforms.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "instruct_c2",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691457",
                "QuestionType": "DB",
                "Selector": "TB",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
                "ChoiceOrder": [],
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed vast state assets, from oil and gas fields to media companies, were privatised rapidly. In theory, privatisation was meant to distribute ownership among citizens in a fairer manner. In practice, however, a small group of well-connected businessmen acquired major enterprises at a fraction of their value.</p>\n           <p>A key moment was the \u201cloans-for-shares\u201d program of the mid-1990s when the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short-term loans in an attempt to manage fiscal crisis.  Insiders with political connections often won these auctions, which consolidated control over the lucrative natural resource industries. Beyond that, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to concentrate quickly.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, heavily dependent on commodities such as oil, gas, and metals, further amplified fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over time the state reclaimed control over key sectors, which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government authority. However, the legacy of rapid privatisation remains. The concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post-Soviet economic landscape.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>An increasing number of companies are migrating to cloud computing platforms, and new research suggests that a major driver of this is fear of being left behind. According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say that their organisation\u2019s investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by concerns about \u201cmissing out\u201d on innovation, competitive advantage, and industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>The benefits of cloud adoption that are usually preferred are cost savings, scalability, and flexibility. However, the study indicates that competition now plays an equally powerful role. Executives are compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting artificial intelligence tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say the \u201cfear of missing out,\u201d or FOMO, reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. As opposed to waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now making proactive technology bets to avoid falling behind faster-moving competitors. Cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation in sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare</p>\n           <p>However, It is assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks, including cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiralling costs. It is advised for firms to check into cloud enthusiasm with clear planning and governance.</p>\n           <p>Ultimately, the cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity - driven more by perception and pressure than by measurable gains.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>There is an echo of pointe shoes and the commands of established instructors, Inside of the marble corridors of the Beijing Dance Academy. The prestigious institution, which was founded in 1954, is well known for China\u2019s best ballet and classical dancers, blending Russian-inspired technique with traditional Chinese aesthetics.</p>\n           <p>Inside, students as young as eleven years old train for hours each day, while also balancing academic studies with long rehearsals. Many of the faculty members who are former principal dancers, emphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression. Li Xinyue says \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d Li Xinyue is a senior instructor at the institution. \u201cWe try teach our students here to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d</p>\n           <p>The academy\u2019s studios walled are covered with mirrors and barres, but also with calligraphy scrolls and framed production images from historic ballets. Recent graduating students have joined leading companies in places like, Shanghai, London, and New York, portraying the school\u2019s growing international reach.</p>\n           <p>Competition for a place at these institutions is grueling. Each year, thousands of students audition for many places, driven by dreams of center stage. As China invests strongly in cultural diplomacy, the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a symbol and training ground of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to increase access for rural and low income applicants next year as they continue sweeping reforms.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691458",
